<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910828-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>910828-0054.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Merck andamp; Co. Creates   Manufacturing Unit   With Global Scope</HL><DATE>08/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   MRK</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)</IN><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RAHWAY, N.J. -- Pharmaceutical giant Merck andamp; Co. said itcreated a new worldwide manufacturing division with more than30% of its employees and about 50% of its assets.   The new Merck Manufacturing Division will unite existingchemical manufacturing, pharmaceutical and biologicalmanufacturing, and corporate engineering, safety andenvironmental operations.</LP><TEXT>   Dr. John L. Zabriskie, senior vice president, will bepresident of the new unit in addition to his currentcorporate duties.   The division will be managed by four senior vicepresidents: David A. Conklin, also president for chemicalmanufacturing; Joseph W. Keating, also president forpharmaceutical manufacturing; Stanley J. Fidelman, in chargeof engineering, safety and the environment; and Bernard J.Kelley, who has been promoted to senior vice president foradministration, planning and quality.   The new division will have 12,550 employees.   A spokeswoman said the new organization was intended to&quot;bring the manufacturing operation more in line with theincreasingly global nature of the business that we do.&quot; Shesaid no work force reductions are anticipated but that &quot;asthe division continues to work together we will be lookingfor additional ways to achieve more efficiencies.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>